Introduction: Text from the following website:https://malucalle.github.io/statistical-pills/coda4microbiome.html

“Understanding the role of the microbiome in human health and how it can be modulated is becoming increasingly relevant for preventive medicine and for the medical management of chronic diseases (Calle 2019).#High-throughput sequencing technologies has boosted microbiome research but the compositional nature of microbiome data is a major challenge for their analysis. Microbiome count data is compositional since their total are constrained by the sequencing depth. Relative abundances (proportions) are obviously constraint by a sum equal to one. This total constraint induces strong dependencies among the observed abundances of the different taxa. In fact, nor the absolute abundance (read counts) nor the relative abundance (proportion) of one taxon alone are informative of the real abundance of the taxon in the environment. Instead, they provide information on the relative measure of abundance when compared to the abundance of other taxa in the same sample. We use a new package, coda4microbiome, that aims to bridge the gap between microbiome research and compositional data analysis (CoDA).

PART#1

We will use the coda_glmnet() function from the code4microbiome R package for Cross-sectional analysis of the following cross-sectional study with categorical binary output response variable relating to disease status (T2D vs. healthy) Data set Qin et al. (2012) Type2 Diabetes microbiome study: https://www.nature.com/articles/nature11450

The algorithm checks if the outcome is binary or continuous. According to this, for a pair of variables A and B, different measures of association between the outcome and the pairwise log-ratio log(A/B) are available: For binary outcomes:“AUC”: Discrimination accuracy (AUC) of the log-ratio log(A/B) for the outcome Y (default) “glm”: Discrimination accuracy (AUC) of the predictions of the logistic regression model glm(y ~log(A/B)+covar)for the outcome Y

#Evidently, the output categorical response variable is "disease"
#However, execution of explore_logratios() function on unfactored "y"variable generated the following error message:
#Error in eval(family$initialize) : y values must be 0 <= y <= 1
#Therefore, the response variable metadata$disease is first factored with levels obtained from the metadata dataframe:
metadata$disease<-factor(metadata$disease, levels=c("healthy","T2D"))

#The coda4microbiome package's function explore_logratios() explores the association of each pairwise log-ratio with the 
#binary "y=metadata$disease categorical dependent response variable. This functions summarizes the importance of each variable (taxa) 
#as the aggregation of the association measures of those log-ratios involving the variable.
#Executing the function explore_logratios():
diabetes_logratios<-explore_logratios(x=x,y=metadata$disease, measure = "glm")

#We now illustrate the coda_glmnet algorithm with the qin.RData dataset
